Kickstarter Campaign Analytics¶

The dataset has been sourced from https://webrobots.io/kickstarter-datasets/. The data has been scraped by a professional web scraping service on a monthly basis. Each monthly dataset consists of multiple csv file zipped together and in total has approx. 200,000 rows and 41 columns. For this coursework, datasets from January 2020 to October 2020 will be used. As each dataset is quite huge and factoring in computation resource limitations, each dataset will be randomly sampled and combined into a larger dataset.

1. Data Wrangling and Processing¶

Instead of unzipping files and extracting over 60 csv files from each zipped folder, python can be used to automate this process. 'file_dir' consists of the file names of each dataset used in this coursework.

In [1]:
#file_dir contains the names of each monthly dataset

    'Kickstarter_2020-01-16T03_20_15_556Z.zip',

Using ZipFile, each dataset will be unzipped and processed. Each dataset is randomly sampled and 30% of each dataset will make up the coursework dataset.

In [2]:
from zipfile import ZipFile
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

data_month_list = []

#Extract the CSV files from each zipped folder and randomly sample 30 percent of its contents. Store them in a list.
for file_name in file_dir:
    zipped_file = ZipFile(file_name)
    partial_data = {file.filename: pd.read_csv(zipped_file.open(file.filename)) for file in zipped_file.infolist()}
    data_month = pd.concat(partial_data, ignore_index = True)
    data_month_rand = data_month.sample(frac=0.3)
    data_month_list.append(data_month_rand)

Concatenate all the files together in a single Pandas dataframe. Dropping any duplicates in the dataset, keeping the latest information about each unique campaign. The data consists of 198772 rows and 41 columns.

In [3]:
data = pd.concat(data_month_list, ignore_index = True)
data = data.drop_duplicates(subset='blurb', keep="last", ignore_index = True)

Some of them are textual/categorical and some numerical columns have only very few null values. Any columns with too many NaNs will be dropped. For instance, the 'friends' column.

data.drop(columns = ['friends', 'is_backing', 'is_starred', 'permissions', 'currency_symbol', 'currency_trailing_code', 'photo', 'usd_type'], inplace = True)

To better capture the extent to which a campaign has performed, a new column 'raised_cap' will be included. This variable will be the excess capital raised over the goal amount. This will give an estimate of how well a campaign has performed. 'raised_percent' will capture the percentage increase.

In [7]:
data['raised_cap'] = data['usd_pledged'] - data['goal_usd']
data['raised_cap'] = round(data['raised_cap'])

data['raised_percent'] = (round(data['usd_pledged']) / round(data['goal_usd'])) * 100

There are four states defining a campaign. It can be successful, a failure, cancelled, or live. A new column 'success' will capture this information. To avoid losing data points, success can be defined as meeting or exceeding the goal amount. A 1 will indicate success and a 0 will indicate failure. Since the reason for a cancelled campaign is not clear, instead of discarding those data points, the data can be classified according to the established criteria. Similarly, any live campaigns that have already exceeded their goal amounts will be included in the dataset. Campaigns that are live but have not yet reached their targets will be discarded due to uncertainty and no appropriate label.

In [8]:
data.loc[data['state'] == 'successful', 'success'] = 1
data.loc[data['state'] == 'failed', 'success'] = 0
data.loc[((data['state'] == 'canceled') & (data['raised_cap'] >= 0)), 'success'] = 1
data.loc[((data['state'] == 'canceled') & (data['raised_cap'] < 0)), 'success'] = 0
data.loc[((data['state'] == 'live') & (data['raised_cap'] >= 0)), 'success'] = 1

Removing misclassified data. The data loss is miniscule.

In [9]:
print("Data size before removing unexplainable points: ", data.shape[0])
if data[(data['raised_cap'] > 0) & (data['success'] == 0)].shape[0] > 0:
    data = data[~((data['raised_cap'] > 0) & (data['success'] == 0))]
if data[(data['raised_cap'] < 0) & (data['success'] == 1)].shape[0] > 0:
    data = data[~((data['raised_cap'] < 0) & (data['success'] == 1))]
print("Data size after removing unexplainable points: ", data.shape[0])

The distribution of goal amounts needs to be analysed. A boxplot and histogram are plotted. As seen in the plots, the data is extremely skewed to the left. Most statistical operations will require normally distributed data, and therefore a log transformation of the variable is performed. After the log transformation, the data is normally distributed, albeit with a mean shifted to the right. Any goal amounts that lie three standard deviations away from the mean will be treated as an outlier and discarded. The plots after discarding outliers are also plotted below.

In [30]:

Backers count is another interesting variable that needs to be analysed. A boxplot and histogram reveals the presense of a huge number of outliers and extreme left skew. The data is log transformed in an attempt to make it more suitable for analysis. However, the log distribution shows a broad bimodal distribution which means that there are two overlapping distributions. The data can be split into successful and failed campaings to see if the data can be better analysed.

3. Detailed Data Exploration¶

To begin with, the proportion of countries that have high success rates needs to be evaluated. Hong Kong, Japan, Singapore, and Great Britain have some of the highest success rates. There is a caveat. The number of campaigns from countries other than the US or GB is quite low and therefore will need to be taken into account.

Linear Regression

Linear regression will be used to understand how the variables such as goal_usd, backers_count, and raised_cap affect each other. As seen in the heatmap earlier, the correlations are quite weak. However, regression analysis might prove to be useful.

The first regression is performed between goal_usd and backers_count. Unfortunately, the R2 is very low suggesting very low variance captured by the model. Pointless to continue the analysis when the R2 is only 0.02

In [50]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression

temp = pd.DataFrame(data['backers_count'])
temp['goal_usd'] = data['goal_usd']

temp['backers_norm'] = temp['backers_count'].transform(np.log)
temp['goal_usd'] = temp['goal_usd'].transform(np.log)
temp = temp[np.isfinite(temp)]
temp = temp.dropna()

model = LinearRegression()

model.fit(temp[['goal_usd']], temp['backers_norm'])
print('intercept:', model.intercept_)
print('slope:', model.coef_)

r_sq=model.score(temp[['goal_usd']], temp['backers_norm'])
print("R2=",r_sq)

intercept: 1.7888451437613446
slope: [0.17664947]
R2= 0.022155928356660026

As seen earlier in the distributions, backers_count is quite normally distributed only when the successful campaigns are considered. The previous model might be failing due to non-linearity and non-normality. A linear regression is done below using a subset of the data. Here an R2 of 0.47 can be observed which definitely warrants further investigation. The residual histogram is normally distributed but the mean is shifted to the left which isnt ideal. The mean squared error is quite high pointing to a weak model. The QQ plot of the residual is mostly normally distributed with most of the points on the normal line. Not an ideal fit. This investigation was carried out in the hopes to understand how a goal amount affects the number of backers. Does a high goal amount deter backers? The model seems to suggest that in the case when the camapigns ae successful, the goal amount does not seem to be an issue for the number of backers. This is to be expected and hardly surprising. A more interesting result would have been obtained if the entire dataset was used.

temp['backers_count'] = temp['backers_count'].transform(np.log)
temp = temp[np.isfinite(temp)]
temp = temp.dropna()

model = LinearRegression()

model.fit(temp[['backers_count']], temp['raised_cap'])
print('intercept:', model.intercept_)
print('slope:', model.coef_)

r_sq=model.score(temp[['backers_count']], temp['raised_cap'])
print("R2=",r_sq)

temp['pred'] = model.predict(temp[['raised_cap']])

temp['resid'] = temp['pred']-temp['raised_cap']

fig, axis = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(15, 5))
axis[0].scatter(temp['backers_count'], temp['raised_cap'],c="#77000022")
axis[0].scatter(temp['raised_cap'], temp['pred'],c="#00770022")
axis[0].set_title('Linear Regression Backers vs Raised Capital')
axis[1].boxplot(temp['resid'])
axis[1].set_title('Boxplot of Residual')
axis[2].hist(temp['resid'],bins=20)
axis[2].set_title('Histogram of Residual')
plt.show()

print("Mean Squared Error {:.3f}".format(mean_squared_error(temp['raised_cap'], temp['pred'])))
print("Mean {:.3f}".format(temp['resid'].mean()))#More readable number
print("Standard devation {:.3f}".format(temp['resid'].std()))#More readable number
print("Mean backers_count {:.3f}".format(temp['raised_cap'].mean()))
print("Median backers_count {:.3f}".format(temp['raised_cap'].median()))

Linear regression analysis was ineffective in this analysis. Perhaps better transformation techniques could have yielded better results. Log transofrmations seem to be inadequate and research into other transformation techniques must be looked into for the future. Perhaps this technique is prone to failure in this analysis as the variables are extremely skewed, are non-normal (backers_count), and have low correlation. Alternative ML techniques can be looked into for better fit.

3. Predictive Modeling - Logistic Regression¶

For building a predictive model to accurately ascertain successful campaigns, this analysis will be looking at categorical variables. Logistic regression will be a very useful technique when it comes to categorical variables. Here, success is the label and interesting categorical variables will be used as data. This technique can showcase the impact categorical variables have on the success of a campaign. A very important point to note is that only certain variables are chosen for this analysis. The variables are known when the project is live. If a predictive model could be built just on such variables that are visible during the launch of a project, the effectiveness and usefulness of the model will increase. Due to complexity and computational limitations, locations of cities are not included as the data set becomes too massive and difficult to model.

x_train_mod, x_test_mod, y_train_mod, y_test_mod = train_test_split(data_logreg.drop('success',axis=1), data_logreg['success'], test_size=0.33, random_state=42)

This model seems to be very promising! It has an accuracy score of 78% and can predict successes with 85% precision and failures with 72% precision. The model seems to predict successful campaigns quite well.
